shire, Scotland":"Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Wernebald was born about 1094, in Scotland as the daughter of De Morville. She married Wernebald De Cunninghame in 1115, in Ayrshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in 1124, at the age of 31."},"et":{"about 1094–1124":"umbes 1094–1124","1094–1124":"1094–1124","1085–1140":"1085–1140","1115–1180":"1115–1180","1122–Male":"1122–Surnud","1123–Male":"1123–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","about 1094":"umbes 1094","1115":"1115","1124":"1124","1123":"1123","1122":"1122","about 1115":"umbes 1115","about 1123":"umbes 1123","1140":"1140","1085":"1085","about 1122":"umbes 1122","1094":"1094","1180":"1180","Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"about 1094–1124":"noin 1094–1124","1094–1124":"1094–1124","1085–1140":"1085–1140","1115–1180":"1115–1180","1122–Male":"1122–Kuollut","1123–Male":"1123–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","about 1094":"noin 1094","1115":"1115","1124":"1124","1123":"112